history.content: I took the class and I will be a TA next semester. The course is difficult, there is a steep learning curve to the languages used in the class. There won't be any exams but there will be frequent projects (medium sized, about 6 of them) and a large final project that you get class time to work on. As of now there is no assigned lab section, but given the small size of the class, we may work something out if it is in the interest of the students.

children.subject:
The shape compiler explores the idea of an engine that translates higher level code into physical shapes and object files that can be interpreted by 3d fabrication machines, as opposed to binary code that is interpreted by CPUs. It's a different style of thinking, and more of a concept and abstraction than anything else. 

We will be writing programs to generate designs for things that will be machined, and you will need a Maker Pass.

I was reading the course info.... what exactly is a shape compiler? 

Will we have the opportunity to build and prototype in the class? I’m assuming it’s mostly programmatic but are we going to write programs to machine things? Will we need a Maker Pass?
Thanks for your response! I was wondering how you would compare the workload/difficulty to CS 186 or another CS upper div? Does it require a strong math background?
